+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Running ${PKGSTEM} on OpenBSD
+-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Start using PM2
===============

The recommended way of Uptime Kuma is by using PM2 which is available in ports
and can be installed via pkg_add(1):

    # pkg_add pm2
    # rcctl start pm2

Uptime-kuma will run with user PM2, database rights must be adjusted:

    # chown -R _pm2:_pm2 ${LOCALSTATEDIR}/db/uptime-kuma/

The configuration file for PM2 should be edited to start uptime-kuma:

    # cat ${SYSCONFDIR}/pm2/ecosystem.config.js
    module.exports = {
      apps : [
        {
          name: "uptime-kuma",
          script: "server/server.js",
          args: "data-dir=${LOCALSTATEDIR}/db/uptime-kuma/",
          cwd: "${TRUEPREFIX}/libexec/uptime-kuma"
        }
      ]
    }

    # rcctl reload pm2

Logs are available in pm2.

    $ doas -u _pm2 tail -f \
        ${LOCALSTATEDIR}/db/pm2/.pm2/logs/uptime-kuma-{error,out}.log
